                        <div class="third last">
                        	<h2>What I do</h2>
<p>
My current research interests include
speech processing, analysis, synthesis and recognition,
dialog and multi-modal systems, lexical semantics, 
natural language understanding, artificial intelligence
behavioral informatics, affective analysis, modelling and recognition,
machine learning and representation learning, 
cognitive semantics,
nonlinear signal processing,
and multimodal child-computer interaction.
I am especially interested on how cognitive semantic reprsentations can
motivate us to create computational models that are robust, accurate and 
rapid learners of multimodal information. 
</p>

<p>
I have authored or co-authored over 140 <a href="publications.htm">papers</a>
in professional journals and conferences (<a href="http://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pBQViyUAAAAJ&hl=en">citations: 3788, h-index: 31, google scholar - Feb 2014</a>).
I was a co-author of the paper
<a href="publications.html#1">"Creating conversational interfaces for children"</a>
that received a 2005 IEEE Signal Processing Society Best Paper Award,
and the co-editor of the book "<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Multimodal-Processing-Interaction-Multimedia-Applications/dp
/0387763155/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1210759074&sr=8-4">Multimodal Processing and Interaction: Audio, Video, Text</a>"
, Springer, 2008.
A list of my patents can be <a href="publications.htm#3">found here</a>.
I have been a member of the <a href="http://ieee.org">IEEE Signal Processing Society</a>
since 1992 and a fellow since 2016. I am 
currently serving my third term  at the <a href="http://www.signalprocessingsociety.org/technical-committees/list/sl-tc/
">IEEE Speech and Language Technical Committee</a>
and my first term at the
<a href="http://www.signalprocessingsociety.org/technical-committees/list/mmsp-tc/">IEEE Multimedia Signal Processing Committee</a>.
</p>

